4.5 stars really -- Overall, a solid fine dining experience from beginning to end. Service that was attentive but not obtrusive, decor that was elegant but not stuffy and food that was nicely presented and full of flavor. Reservations are relatively easy to come by and prices are relatively reasonable. Oh -- and ask for one of their purse hooks before you leave. They'll give you a brand new one, free of charge. So why not the full 5 stars? Like others have said, perhaps it was the expectation. Or perhaps (as others have also said), one can't help but compare Gary Danko to other top Bay Area restaurants -- The French Laundry, Cyrus, etc -- and in comparison, GD fell a little short. Food - I hate to say this because it'll make me sound like a snob but here it is: the food seemed a bit . . . pedestrian. Not the way it was prepared or the way it tasted, but the menu items themelves. There was nothing inspiring or creative or innovative. Now, I'm not one of those people that like creativity for the sake of creativity, but I would've liked to feel like I was trying something I'd never had before; if not the food itself, then the way it was executed or paired with other ingredients. Seared foie? Check. Seared scallops? Check. Lobster risotto? Check. Seared tuna? Check. Filet of beef? Check. You get the idea. Everything on the menu was "safe", except a pancetta-wrapped frog leg, but even that falls within the "traditional" realm in French cuisine. That being said, what GD does, they do extremely well, and if you're new to fine dining, GD is a great place to start. The menu is flexible, the food is familiar, and the service is not at all intimidating. Service - There were some very, very minor things that were a little bothersome: (1) Someone at our table had an empty wine glass for a long time before anyone came to refill it. I would've done it myself but I always feel bad doing that because I know it makes the servers feel bad (twisted logic, I know). (2) Bread refills were also slow to come by. (3) And this bothered me the most -- one person in our 6-person party did the 3-course, whereas the rest of us did the 4-course. As a result, there was a course early on where all of us had something in front of us except her. It would've been nice to give her something to nibble on while the rest of us were eating, which I've seen at other restaurants. I know I'm being very nitpicky here, but it's only because I'm holding GD to an extremely high standard. And I know this sounds like a negative review, but it's really not. I would still highly recommend GD to out-of-towners and for special occasions, and I do plan to return. P.S. My now-husband and I dined at GD years ago, when they first opened and when we were still in our early-20's. We kept commenting that we couldn't remember that much about the meal even though we didn't think it was bad, and I thought it was just because our tastes weren't as refined back then; we were fine dining novices at the time. But now after writing my review, I think the reason it wasn't memorable was because the menu is so "safe" as I mentioned above.

Reviewing a fine dinning restaurant is no simple task. When you enter the higher eschelon of dinning, a very different gastronomic experience presents itself. Take for instance the square cube of ice in my cocktail. This was no ordinary square piece of ice - it was as wide as the glass - and about an inch thick. Yes it was displacing potential booze volume, but in combination with the skillfully prepared cocktail, it was very suave. My visit to Gary Danko was to celebrate 34 years of an interesting life. I was accompanied by one special person - my girlfriend. We're not the flushest of folk, so we were watching our spend. We decided to go for the three course tasting menu, and to share our plates - so we thriftily had a six course tasting menu. Our bill including tip came to about $280. The food was indeed very good. The best quality ingredients at use, combined with modern cooking techniques, with a California/French style. There is a trend in bay area restaurants for poor acoustics. With all the money and expense probably paid for the interior design of GD, one would have thought they could have paid attention to the acoustic design. The restaurant was just too noisy for a fine dinning establishment. Hopefully when they undertake a refit, they can take a more holistic approach to the fine dinning experience. The restrooms were also a bit scruffy. If you're in a party of two, I would request a table in the dinning room that does not have the bar. This is where we sat, and the acoustics were tolerable. Overall a great experience at Gary Danko. I'll certainly go back... when I have the spare cash.

    3/1/2009

    4.5 stars really -- Overall, a solid fine dining experience from beginning to end. Service that was attentive but not obtrusive, decor that was elegant but not stuffy and food that was nicely presented and full of flavor. Reservations are relatively easy to come by and prices are relatively reasonable. Oh -- and ask for one of their purse hooks before you leave. They'll give you a brand new one, free of charge.

    So why not the full 5 stars? Like others have said, perhaps it was the expectation. Or perhaps (as others have also said), one can't help but compare Gary Danko to other top Bay Area restaurants -- The French Laundry, Cyrus, etc -- and in comparison, GD fell a little short.

    Food - I hate to say this because it'll make me sound like a snob but here it is: the food seemed a bit . . . pedestrian. Not the way it was prepared or the way it tasted, but the menu items themelves. There was nothing inspiring or creative or innovative. Now, I'm not one of those people that like creativity for the sake of creativity, but I would've liked to feel like I was trying something I'd never had before; if not the food itself, then the way it was executed or paired with other ingredients. Seared foie? Check. Seared scallops? Check. Lobster risotto? Check. Seared tuna? Check. Filet of beef? Check. You get the idea. Everything on the menu was "safe", except a pancetta-wrapped frog leg, but even that falls within the "traditional" realm in French cuisine.

    That being said, what GD does, they do extremely well, and if you're new to fine dining, GD is a great place to start. The menu is flexible, the food is familiar, and the service is not at all intimidating.

    Service - There were some very, very minor things that were a little bothersome: (1) Someone at our table had an empty wine glass for a long time before anyone came to refill it. I would've done it myself but I always feel bad doing that because I know it makes the servers feel bad (twisted logic, I know). (2) Bread refills were also slow to come by. (3) And this bothered me the most -- one person in our 6-person party did the 3-course, whereas the rest of us did the 4-course. As a result, there was a course early on where all of us had something in front of us except her. It would've been nice to give her something to nibble on while the rest of us were eating, which I've seen at other restaurants.

    I know I'm being very nitpicky here, but it's only because I'm holding GD to an extremely high standard. And I know this sounds like a negative review, but it's really not. I would still highly recommend GD to out-of-towners and for special occasions, and I do plan to return.

    P.S. My now-husband and I dined at GD years ago, when they first opened and when we were still in our early-20's. We kept commenting that we couldn't remember that much about the meal even though we didn't think it was bad, and I thought it was just because our tastes weren't as refined back then; we were fine dining novices at the time. But now after writing my review, I think the reason it wasn't memorable was because the menu is so "safe" as I mentioned above.
